              <section>

                  
          <div data-content-element-selector="p, .js-buylink-item-container" data-allowed-classes-selector="js-buylink-item-container">
                <p dir="ltr">With <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/articles/oblivion-remaster-surprise-launches-today-on-game-pass/1100-6530669/">the surprise launch of Oblivion Remastered</a> last week, there has been speculation about whether Bethesda Game Studios might use the older RPG as the foundation for <a href="https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-elder-scrolls-6-release-date-trailer-news/1100-6492383/">The Elder Scrolls VI</a> instead of the more streamlined Skyrim. Bruce Nesmith, a developer on the original Elder Scrolls IV, doesn't believe that will be the case.</p><p dir="ltr">Speaking with <a href="https://www.videogamer.com/features/elder-scrolls-6-not-drowned-in-stats-focus-on-real-choices/" rel="nofollow ">VideoGamer</a>, Nesmith suggested player choices should trump stat management in The Elder Scrolls VI. "We donâ€™t want the game to get in the way," said the former Bethesda developer. "And that's a very modern take on RPGs. And that is actually at the heart of the 'you do it to get better at it' [leveling mechanic] philosophy of The Elder Scrolls. Because that means I'm not having to pick my skills, I just play. Don't worry about all that crap if you donâ€™t want to."</p><div tabindex="0" data-id="461252385" data-promo-id="0" data-user-has-ads="1" data-video="{&quot;id&quot;:6465911,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;The%20Oblivion%20Situation%20%7C%20The%20GameSpot%20Show&quot;,&quot;lengthSeconds&quot;:1752,&quot;startTime&quot;:0,&quot;autoplay&quot;:false,&quot;share&quot;:{&quot;linkUrl&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/www.gamespot.com\/videos\/the-oblivion-situation-the-gamespot-show\/2300-6465911\/&quot;,&quot;embedUrl&quot;:&quot;https:\/\/www.gamespot.com\/videos\/embed\/6465911\/&quot;,&quot;embedHtml&quot;:{&quot;640&quot;:&quot;\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<iframe src=\&quot;https:\/\/www.gamespot.com\/videos\/embed\/6465911\/\&quot; height=\&quot;360\&quot; width=\&quot;640\&quot; scrolling=\&quot;no\&quot; frameborder=\&quot;\&quot; webkitAllowFullScreen mozall